    "explanation": "A is correct. The cardinal distinguishing feature of delirium versus dementia is the TIME COURSE: Delirium is ACUTE in onset (hours to days), FLUCTUATES (waxes and wanes over the course of a day), and is characterized by impaired ATTENTION (inability to focus, sustain, or shift attention). This patient had normal baseline function and acutely developed confusion — classic delirium. Dementia has insidious onset over months to years, is progressive but not fluctuating, and attention is relatively preserved until late stages. B is incorrect: hallucinations can occur in both delirium and dementia (especially Lewy body dementia). C is incorrect: memory impairment is the HALLMARK of dementia, not delirium. D is incorrect: disorientation occurs in both conditions.",
