    "id": 100,
    "category": "Mental Health",
    "subcategory": "Mental Health Principles",
    "stem": "A 25-year-old man with schizophrenia is followed in primary care. He is on risperidone. His weight has increased 22 lbs in 6 months, his fasting glucose is 118 mg/dL, BP is 138/88 mmHg, and his waist circumference is 42 inches. His mental health provider has not been checking metabolic parameters. What does this constellation of findings represent, and whose responsibility is its management?",
    "options": [
      "These are expected side effects of antipsychotics and do not require intervention",
      "The patient should be taken off risperidone immediately to reverse the metabolic changes",
      "These findings are unrelated to his psychiatric medications and should be evaluated as separate, coincidental conditions",
      "Metabolic syndrome secondary to antipsychotic therapy — primary care and mental health providers share responsibility for monitoring and management"
    ],
    "correct": 3,
    "explanation": "D is correct. Atypical antipsychotics (especially olanzapine, clozapine, quetiapine, risperidone) are strongly associated with metabolic syndrome — weight gain, hyperglycemia/insulin resistance, dyslipidemia, and hypertension. This patient's findings (weight gain, pre-diabetes, elevated BP, increased waist circumference) meet criteria for metabolic syndrome. Monitoring metabolic parameters is a SHARED responsibility between mental health and primary care providers — if mental health is not monitoring these parameters, primary care should. This is a priority clinical issue as metabolic syndrome leads to cardiovascular disease, type 2 diabetes, and significantly reduced life expectancy in patients with serious mental illness. A is incorrect: these are not merely 'expected' — they require active management. C is incorrect: the temporal relationship with antipsychotic initiation and the constellation of metabolic changes make antipsychotic-induced metabolic syndrome the clear explanation. B is incorrect: abruptly discontinuing antipsychotics risks psychiatric decompensation; the risks and benefits must be weighed, and medication adjustment (if indicated) requires psychiatric guidance.",
    "source": "Module 12 - Psychosocial and Mental Health Disorders",
