    "explanation": "A is correct: This stable HFrEF patient is on an ACE inhibitor and diuretic but is missing a beta-blocker, which is a cornerstone of guideline-directed medical therapy (GDMT). Beta-blockers (carvedilol, metoprolol succinate, bisoprolol) are proven to reduce mortality and hospitalizations in HFrEF. When a patient on an ACEi + diuretic has persistent fatigue, the next GDMT step is to add a beta-blocker — not to escalate diuretics. B is incorrect: Increasing furosemide may temporarily improve symptoms of fluid overload but does not reduce mortality. The patient shows mild crackles but is stable and not in acute decompensation; diuresis escalation is not the priority when a mortality-reducing drug is still missing from the regimen. C is incorrect: Adding an MRA (spironolactone) is the step after both ACEi and beta-blocker have been optimized. The patient is not yet on a beta-blocker, so spironolactone would be added later in the sequence. D is incorrect: Transitioning to ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan) is appropriate for certain patients with HFrEF already on ACEi, but adding the missing beta-blocker is the immediate priority per GDMT sequencing guidelines.",
